<P N="12">12. And now let us turn a&s;ide and &s;ee this great &s;ight. Let us &s;tand &s;till and con&s;ider this &s;olemn &s;cene here open|ed to our view! By the help of that faith which is the evidence of things not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">een, let us contemplate the aw|ful maje&s;ty and terrible grandeur of that day, if our weak &s;en&s;es can endure the dreadful glory of it's light, or our feeble faculties &s;u&s;tain the effulgence of its over-power|ing brightne&s;s and a&s;toni&s;hing terrors.&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">h! how <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t it &s;urprize and alarm the &s;ecure &s;inner, and how mu&s;t it &s;trike all men with amazement and awe, in the dead of night, to be &s;uddenly awaked out of the repo&s;e of their la&s;t &s;leep, by the confu&s;ed noi&s;e and deafening rour of trumpets &s;ounding, thunders grumbling, &s;tars ru&s;hing, elements melting, waves da&s;hing, the &s;ea to&s;&s;ing, and the earth quaking! Ah! how will the &s;toute&s;t heart fail for fear, and &s;ink with horrible dread, to hear the &s;udden
<PB N="22" REF="031758_0022_0FEE31016E851690"><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ru&s;h of worlds, and behold the wreck of univer&s;al na|ture! To &s;ee
